00:34:21.739 --> 00:34:24.610
talking about the
power of storytelling.

00:34:24.610 --> 00:34:27.380
Because stories connect us.

00:34:27.380 --> 00:34:30.679
They create that burning
desire to learn about others.

00:34:30.679 --> 00:34:33.570
And every single one
of us have a story.

00:34:33.570 --> 00:34:35.570
A lot of times, we make
assumptions about people

00:34:35.570 --> 00:34:37.370
when we meet and see them.

00:34:37.370 --> 00:34:42.310
And human beings have that story
that create that connection.

00:34:42.310 --> 00:34:45.860
And so learning that
story is powerful currency

00:34:45.860 --> 00:34:49.310
for understanding each other
and creating that inspiration

00:34:49.310 --> 00:34:50.630
and getting that hope--

00:34:50.630 --> 00:34:53.250
and understanding the
resilience of human beings.

00:34:53.250 --> 00:34:56.010
So I'm just going to share
with you my personal story.

00:34:56.010 --> 00:34:59.780
My parents were married
at the tender age of 19.

00:34:59.780 --> 00:35:02.720
And I often say that the path
to the Chief Diversity Officer

00:35:02.720 --> 00:35:05.480
role at Walmart started
long before I was born.

00:35:05.480 --> 00:35:08.750
It started with my parents and
what their lives were like.

00:35:08.750 --> 00:35:12.690
So much to the disappointment
of both sets of my grandparents,

00:35:12.690 --> 00:35:14.520
my parents decide
to get married.

00:35:14.520 --> 00:35:16.910
They were from very different
religious backgrounds

00:35:16.910 --> 00:35:19.730
and very different
socioeconomic backgrounds.

00:35:19.730 --> 00:35:24.020
And so, as I grew up, I listened
to very negative comments

00:35:24.020 --> 00:35:27.050
when we'd get together
with our relatives.

00:35:27.050 --> 00:35:30.740
My family on my father's
side were very disappointed

00:35:30.740 --> 00:35:32.960
that my father chose my mother.

00:35:32.960 --> 00:35:35.330
My mother's side-- they
thought my father's family

00:35:35.330 --> 00:35:36.980
was arrogant and out of touch.

00:35:36.980 --> 00:35:38.870
So we always heard
these negative things.

00:35:38.870 --> 00:35:39.980
And I don't know
about your family,

00:35:39.980 --> 00:35:41.330
but when our family'd
get together,

00:35:41.330 --> 00:35:43.872
they'd just tell it the way it
is, regardless of how negative

00:35:43.872 --> 00:35:45.230
it was or bad.

00:35:45.230 --> 00:35:49.730
So my parents made a very
purposeful parenting decision

00:35:49.730 --> 00:35:52.370
to move away from
relatives, because they

00:35:52.370 --> 00:35:55.580
wanted to stop that negative
stereotypes of comments

00:35:55.580 --> 00:35:56.387
that occurred.

00:35:56.387 --> 00:35:58.220
So I grew up believing
that you should never

00:35:58.220 --> 00:35:59.690
live near your relatives.

00:35:59.690 --> 00:36:01.850
So we moved thousands
of miles away.

00:36:01.850 --> 00:36:04.640
And we only saw them
because we had to see them.

00:36:04.640 --> 00:36:06.650
But that experience
with my parents

00:36:06.650 --> 00:36:10.550
made them very strong advocates
of the Civil Rights movement

00:36:10.550 --> 00:36:12.170
and the Women's Rights movement.

00:36:12.170 --> 00:36:13.940
So they made another
parenting decision.

00:36:13.940 --> 00:36:15.990
When I was 12 years
old, they moved us

00:36:15.990 --> 00:36:17.990
to a neighborhood that
was predominantly African

00:36:17.990 --> 00:36:19.645
American and Hispanic.

00:36:19.645 --> 00:36:21.020
So we moved to
this neighborhood.

00:36:21.020 --> 00:36:22.670
And we were not welcome.

00:36:22.670 --> 00:36:24.860
So we had our yard set on fire.

00:36:24.860 --> 00:36:27.110
Our home was vandalized
several times.

00:36:27.110 --> 00:36:29.300
My parents owned a small
landscaping business

00:36:29.300 --> 00:36:31.130
that was also vandalized.

00:36:31.130 --> 00:36:32.870
But I was never afraid.

00:36:32.870 --> 00:36:34.480
I was 12 years old.

00:36:34.480 --> 00:36:36.420
And I just wanted
to make friends.

00:36:36.420 --> 00:36:38.045
I wanted to know,
who am I going to sit

00:36:38.045 --> 00:36:41.130
with on the school bus every
single day when I go to school?

00:36:41.130 --> 00:36:44.570
And so our family lived in
that neighborhood for 30 years.

00:36:44.570 --> 00:36:48.380
And what it taught me is that
we're all more similar than we

00:36:48.380 --> 00:36:49.740
are different.

00:36:49.740 --> 00:36:51.690
We all want to be respected.

00:36:51.690 --> 00:36:53.220
We want to be included.

00:36:53.220 --> 00:36:55.410
And we want to be valued.

00:36:55.410 --> 00:36:59.570
And so that created in me
this core belief that we all

00:36:59.570 --> 00:37:01.720
deserve respect and inclusion.

00:37:01.720 --> 00:37:03.290
And that's what led
me to all my work

00:37:03.290 --> 00:37:04.620
in diversity and inclusion.

00:37:04.620 --> 00:37:08.300
But it started with my parents
and what they did for me.

00:37:08.300 --> 00:37:10.010
We're going talk a
little bit about why

00:37:10.010 --> 00:37:11.630
stories are so important.

00:37:11.630 --> 00:37:14.140
And some of it is because
they're so memorable.

00:37:14.140 --> 00:37:15.730
We'll go to the next slide.

00:37:15.730 --> 00:37:17.480
You're always going
to remember the story.

00:37:17.480 --> 00:37:19.580
You may not remember
the data or the facts.

00:37:19.580 --> 00:37:20.840
But you're going to
remember those stories that

00:37:20.840 --> 00:37:21.465
stick with you.

00:37:21.465 --> 00:37:23.400
A lot of things that
Thuhang shared today,

00:37:23.400 --> 00:37:25.567
you're going to go home and
share with other people,

00:37:25.567 --> 00:37:27.190
because it really
reminds you of that.

00:37:27.190 --> 00:37:29.720
And when you think
about things at work

00:37:29.720 --> 00:37:31.760
and you're presenting
pitches or ideas

00:37:31.760 --> 00:37:35.480
or thinking about-- how do
you put it in a story format

00:37:35.480 --> 00:37:37.130
that people remember?

00:37:37.130 --> 00:37:39.140
And I know, Google's
big on data.

00:37:39.140 --> 00:37:39.927
I know that.

00:37:39.927 --> 00:37:41.510
Math and science are
really important.

00:37:41.510 --> 00:37:42.780
Logic's important.

00:37:42.780 --> 00:37:45.530
But there's also that
emotional content.

00:37:45.530 --> 00:37:48.540
And stories are
emotion in motion.

00:37:48.540 --> 00:37:50.000
So how do you link
a story to what

00:37:50.000 --> 00:37:52.790
you're trying to sell at work
and make it more understandable

00:37:52.790 --> 00:37:53.700
and more relatable?

00:37:53.700 --> 00:37:56.695
I think it's important, because
stories touch the heart.

00:37:56.695 --> 00:37:58.070
And when you touch
the heart, you

00:37:58.070 --> 00:37:59.480
change the way people think.

00:37:59.480 --> 00:38:01.185
And you change the behaviors.

00:38:01.185 --> 00:38:02.310
So we'll go the next slide.

00:38:02.310 --> 00:38:04.110
And it talks about the
different types of stories.

00:38:04.110 --> 00:38:05.943
So when you're telling
stories, particularly

00:38:05.943 --> 00:38:08.732
at work or at events, there's
a couple of different genres.

00:38:08.732 --> 00:38:10.940
And you'll hear leaders that
share them this way too.

00:38:10.940 --> 00:38:13.255
So one of the main
stories is who am I?

00:38:13.255 --> 00:38:14.630
So when there's
a new leader that

00:38:14.630 --> 00:38:15.920
comes to a group,
a lot of times,

00:38:15.920 --> 00:38:18.110
you'll hear who they are,
what's important to them,

00:38:18.110 --> 00:38:19.700
life experiences
that they've had.

00:38:19.700 --> 00:38:21.990
Or they may talk
about why I'm here.

00:38:21.990 --> 00:38:22.830
What's my purpose?

00:38:22.830 --> 00:38:24.530
What do I hope to do?

00:38:24.530 --> 00:38:26.270
They'll talk about
values and action--

00:38:26.270 --> 00:38:29.150
what their core values are and
how they demonstrate those.

00:38:29.150 --> 00:38:30.500
Then, also-- vision.

00:38:30.500 --> 00:38:32.670
And then there's
teaching stories.

00:38:32.670 --> 00:38:35.630
So what I'm going to close with
is a vision and action story.

00:38:35.630 --> 00:38:38.243
So I've told you a
lot about growing up

00:38:38.243 --> 00:38:40.160
and my passion around
diversity and inclusion.

00:38:40.160 --> 00:38:41.550
So we'll go to the next slide.

00:38:41.550 --> 00:38:44.840
And this is what I call
"The Swimming Pool" story.

00:38:44.840 --> 00:38:46.610
So I lived in
Arkansas for 12 years,

00:38:46.610 --> 00:38:48.050
while I worked with Walmart.

00:38:48.050 --> 00:38:50.230
And my whole life,
I've been passionate

00:38:50.230 --> 00:38:51.550
about diversity and inclusion.

00:38:51.550 --> 00:38:53.945
I feel like my parents did
an incredible job, moving us

00:38:53.945 --> 00:38:55.820
to the neighborhood
where we looked different

00:38:55.820 --> 00:38:57.200
than everybody else.

00:38:57.200 --> 00:38:59.880
So I've wanted to do the
same with my children.

00:38:59.880 --> 00:39:03.440
And so we've done a lot of
diversity immersion trips.

00:39:03.440 --> 00:39:06.343
We invite a lot of very
different people to our homes.

00:39:06.343 --> 00:39:08.510
Four times a year, I used
to invite about 200 people

00:39:08.510 --> 00:39:10.880
to our home from Walmart who
were from different countries

00:39:10.880 --> 00:39:11.963
and different backgrounds.

00:39:11.963 --> 00:39:14.940
And I was always very
purposeful on what we did.

00:39:14.940 --> 00:39:17.990
But my main message to my
kids has always been, speak up

00:39:17.990 --> 00:39:19.250
and speak out.

00:39:19.250 --> 00:39:21.870
If you see something that's not
right, do something about it--

00:39:21.870 --> 00:39:22.370
right?

00:39:22.370 --> 00:39:22.940
Speak up.

00:39:22.940 --> 00:39:23.523
And speak out.

00:39:23.523 --> 00:39:26.300
That's what everybody
is obligated to do.

00:39:26.300 --> 00:39:29.150
So one day in Arkansas, I'm
at a community swimming pool.

00:39:29.150 --> 00:39:30.770
It's Memorial Day weekend.

00:39:30.770 --> 00:39:33.358
And I have my 12-year-old
daughter with me.

00:39:33.358 --> 00:39:34.400
And she's a good swimmer.

00:39:34.400 --> 00:39:35.450
So I'll start with that.

00:39:35.450 --> 00:39:37.400
So she jumps into the pool.

00:39:37.400 --> 00:39:40.470
And I lay down on a lawn
chair and go to sleep.

00:39:40.470 --> 00:39:41.780
That's bad parenting.

00:39:41.780 --> 00:39:43.663
But there is a lifeguard.

00:39:43.663 --> 00:39:45.080
And my daughter
is a good swimmer.

00:39:45.080 --> 00:39:48.290
And I needed a break
from a long week at work.

00:39:48.290 --> 00:39:49.130
So I'm sleeping.

00:39:49.130 --> 00:39:51.320
I'm kind of dozing in and out.

00:39:51.320 --> 00:39:56.000
And I hear this man yell,
why don't you morons get out

00:39:56.000 --> 00:39:56.950
of the pool?!

00:39:56.950 --> 00:39:59.180
Now, when we had walked
into the pool area,

00:39:59.180 --> 00:40:01.880
all of the children in
the pool were white,

00:40:01.880 --> 00:40:04.700
except for two
African-Americans.

00:40:04.700 --> 00:40:07.730
So I heard that man yell that.

00:40:07.730 --> 00:40:08.660
I kind of woke up.

00:40:08.660 --> 00:40:10.130
I sat up.

00:40:10.130 --> 00:40:11.750
And I looked in the pool.

00:40:11.750 --> 00:40:14.480
And I didn't see the
African-American children.

00:40:14.480 --> 00:40:15.920
So I motioned my daughter over.

00:40:15.920 --> 00:40:17.750
And I said, what just happened?

00:40:17.750 --> 00:40:20.540
And she reiterated
what the man had said.

00:40:20.540 --> 00:40:25.280
So in that moment, I
have a lot going on.

00:40:25.280 --> 00:40:28.910
Am I going to do what I've told
my children for years and years

00:40:28.910 --> 00:40:31.430
about speak up and speak out?

00:40:31.430 --> 00:40:33.800
Or am I going to be silent?

00:40:33.800 --> 00:40:35.120
And this is in a community--

00:40:35.120 --> 00:40:36.710
I don't know the
man that yelled it.

00:40:36.710 --> 00:40:39.080
I don't know anybody
else at the pool.

00:40:39.080 --> 00:40:41.310
What am I going to do?

00:40:41.310 --> 00:40:43.350
And so I thought about,
what am I going to do?

00:40:43.350 --> 00:40:47.570
And I decided that I was going
to address the man separately,

00:40:47.570 --> 00:40:49.970
after the holiday
weekend was over.

00:40:49.970 --> 00:40:53.090
So on Tuesday, after
Memorial Day weekend,

00:40:53.090 --> 00:40:55.730
I drove to the
swimming pool area.

00:40:55.730 --> 00:40:57.897
And it was only me and
him that were there.

00:40:57.897 --> 00:40:59.480
And I hadn't told
my husband or people

00:40:59.480 --> 00:41:00.850
at work where I was going to.

00:41:00.850 --> 00:41:02.120
But I walk into this building.

00:41:02.120 --> 00:41:03.395
He's sitting by this desk.

00:41:03.395 --> 00:41:05.270
I said, hey, I want to
talk to you about what

00:41:05.270 --> 00:41:07.040
happened on Saturday?

00:41:07.040 --> 00:41:09.890
I said, did you say, why don't
you morons get out of the pool?

00:41:09.890 --> 00:41:12.090
And he jumps up from the desk.

00:41:12.090 --> 00:41:14.367
He says, are you
calling me a racist?!

00:41:14.367 --> 00:41:15.950
And my first thought
was, nobody knows

00:41:15.950 --> 00:41:19.250
I'm in this building
with this man by myself.

00:41:19.250 --> 00:41:21.320
And I thought long and
hard about-- how do I

00:41:21.320 --> 00:41:23.790
reply to his question?

00:41:23.790 --> 00:41:27.110
So I said, I'm not
calling you a racist.

00:41:27.110 --> 00:41:29.330
But I'm concerned
about how it made

00:41:29.330 --> 00:41:33.950
all the children and everybody
feel when you yelled that.

00:41:33.950 --> 00:41:37.910
So he proceeded to tell me that
he calls Hispanics "morons."

00:41:37.910 --> 00:41:39.440
He calls women "morons."

00:41:39.440 --> 00:41:42.830
He was what I would call an
equal employment offender.

00:41:42.830 --> 00:41:45.320
He let me know, that's
his approach on life.

00:41:45.320 --> 00:41:47.420
So I tried to explain
my point of view.

00:41:47.420 --> 00:41:49.670
He tried to explain
his point of view.

00:41:49.670 --> 00:41:52.040
We ended the
conversation with neither

00:41:52.040 --> 00:41:55.080
of us agreeing with each
other's point of view.

00:41:55.080 --> 00:42:01.537
So two years later, I went back
to that pool with my daughter.

00:42:01.537 --> 00:42:03.620
It had been two years since
I'd been at that pool.

00:42:03.620 --> 00:42:04.703
My daughter and I walk in.

